   <standOff>
      <listNym type="chemical">
         <nym xml:id="chemical_143">
            <form>nitric acid</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: HNO3</p>
               <p>A highly corrosive mineral acid. The compound is colourless, but samples tend to acquire a yellow cast over time due to decomposition into oxides of nitrogen</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_010">
            <form>lime</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: CaO</p>
               <p>Commonly known as quicklime or burnt lime, calcium oxide is a widely used chemical compound. It is a white, caustic, alkaline, crystalline solid at room temperature.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_417">
            <form>sulphuric acid</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: H2SO3</p>
               <p>A mineral acid composed of the elements sulphur, oxygen, and hydrogen. It is a colourless, odourless, and viscous liquid that is miscible with water.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_012">
            <form>mercury</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Hg</p>
               <p>Also known as quicksilver. A heavy, silvery element, mercury is the only metallic element that is known to be liquid at standard temperature and pressure.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_406">
            <form>calcite</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: CaCO3</p>
               <p>Calcite is a carbonate mineral and the most stable polymorph of calcium carbonate. Davy refers to it as Calcareous Spar.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_204">
            <form>lixivium</form>
            <def>
               <p>A chemical used in hydrometallurgy to extract elements from its ore.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_003">
            <form>ammonia</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: NH3</p>
               <p>An inorganic chemical compound of nitrogen and hydrogen. Ammonia is a colourless gas with a distinct pungent smell.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_016">
            <form>muriatic acid</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: HCl</p>
               <p>Hydrochloric acid. Davy also refers to this as muriatic gas and marine acid.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_142">
            <form>nitrous gas</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: NO</p>
               <p>Also nitrous air. Usually this term referred to nitric oxide. Davy used the term nitric phosoxyd to refer to this.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_022">
            <form>oxygene</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: O</p>
               <p>Now known as oxygen. Oxygen is a colourless, odourless, tasteless gas essential to living organisms.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_048">
            <form>nitrous oxide</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: N2O</p>
               <p>Later known as 'laughing gas'. Davy discovered that nitrous oxide was respirable when not contaminated with nitric oxide (NO). Davy researched into the physiological effects of nitrous oxide.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_176">
            <form>isinglass</form>
            <def>
               <p>A substance obtained from the dried swim-bladders of fish. It is a form of collagen used mainly for the clarification or fining of some beer and wine.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_014">
            <form>muriate of lime</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: CaCl2</p>
               <p>An inorganic compound and a white crystalline solid at room temperature. Calcium chloride is highly soluble in water, and can be created by neutralising hydrochloric acid with calcium hydroxide.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_187">
            <form>bismuth</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Bi</p>
               <p>A high-density, silvery, pink-tinged metal.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_151">
            <form>phosphorus</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: P</p>
               <p>A non-metallic chemical element of the nitrogen family. A colourless, semitransparent, soft, waxy solid.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_169">
            <form>oxymuriate of potash</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: KClO3</p>
               <p>Potassium chlorate.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_038">
            <form>tin</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Sn</p>
               <p>A silvery-coloured metal, tin is soft enough to be cut with little force, and a bar of tin can be bent by hand with little effort.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_011">
            <form>magnesia</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: MgO</p>
               <p>A white hygroscopic solid mineral that occurs naturally as periclase and is a source of magnesium.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_030">
            <form>potash</form>
            <def>
               <p>An alkaline substance consisting largely of impure potassium carbonate. In October 1807, Davy decomposed potash using electricity, revealing the previously unknown element potassium.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_296">
            <form>fluoboric gas</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: BF3</p>
               <p>Boron trifluoride. A corrosive gas produced by the action of hydrofluoric acid on boron oxides.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_058">
            <form>carbonic acid</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: CO2 or H2CO3 </p>
               <p>Now known as Carbon dioxide (CO2), or a solution of carbon dioxide in water (H2CO3). </p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_087">
            <form>oil of vitriol</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: H2SO4</p>
               <p>Sulphuric acid. A mineral acid composed of the elements sulphur, oxygen, and hydrogen.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_190">
            <form>barytes</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: BaSO4</p>
               <p>Now known as barium sulphate (BaSO4), a white crystalline solid, occurring as the mineral barites.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_035">
            <form>soda</form>
            <def>
               <p>An alkaline substance obtained from the ashes of marine or salt-impregnated plants, especially species of Salsola. Davy decomposed soda to reveal its elemental sodium.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_108">
            <form>alumine</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: AL2O3</p>
               <p>Alumine is an archaic name for alumina, which is aluminium oxide.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_324">
            <form>tourmaline </form>
            <def>
               <p>Tourmaline is a boron silicate. Opaque and black in colour, tourmaline is a semi-precious stone that can be found in a variety of colours based on the presence of iron, magnesium, or lithium. Boron was first isolated by Davy in 1808.  </p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_358">
            <form>boracite</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Mg(3)B(7)O(13)Cl</p>
               <p>A magnesium borate chloride mineral. </p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_325">
            <form>barium</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Ba</p>
               <p>Davy was the first to isolate barium, using electrochemistry, in 1808. It is a soft, silvery alkaline earth metal, which due to its high chemical reactivity is never found in nature as a free element. </p>
            </def>
         </nym>
      </listNym>
